<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Stonewall is pleased to respond to the consultation paper ‘Getting it right for victims and witnesses’</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Stonewall (BTO0017)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Stonewall is pleased to respond to the House of Commons Select Committee Inquiry into ‘Blood, tissue and organ screening’. Stonewall is an organisation that has campaigned for the 3.6 million lesbian, gay and bisexual people across Britain since 1989. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Stonewall has developed significant expertise on healthcare issues affecting lesbian, gay and bisexual people. This includes undertaking the world's largest survey on the health of gay and bisexual men, the Gay and Bisexual Men's Health Survey (2012)</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and Europe’s largest survey on the health of lesbian and bisexual women, Prescription for Change (2008)</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Stonewall campaigned actively for the lifting of the blanket ban on blood donation from men who have sex with other men. We welcomed the Department of Health’s decision to overturn the lifetime ban in 2011 as a step in the right direction.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> However we are still concerned that under the present system gay and bisexual men engaged in low-risk sexual activity are excluded from giving blood while heterosexual people engaged in higher risk activity are not. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Stonewall continues to push for a blood donation system based on the real risks each potential donor poses. People wanting to donate blood should be asked similar questions - irrespective of their sexual orientation - that accurately assess their </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">risk of infection. This is better for the safety of the blood supply, it is fair, and it is non-discriminatory.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Stonewall response</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The National Blood Service currently enforces a one year deferral from blood donation for any man who has had sex with another man. They believe this is necessary because men who have sex with men pose a higher risk to the blood supply. All donated blood does undergo a screening process. However, the National Blood Service believes that there will always be a risk that an infection can pass undetected.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Gay and bisexual men are not automatically at a higher risk of contracting sexually transmitted infections. The risk instead comes from the practices attributed to gay men, such as unprotected sex and promiscuity. Yet heterosexual people can engage in risky sexual behaviour too. They can be HIV-positive and have sexually transmitted infections in the same way that gay and bisexual men can. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Under the current system many gay and bisexual men who don’t engage in high-risk sexual behaviour are prohibited from giving blood while heterosexual men and women are not asked about their sexual behaviour. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There are a number of countries that have adopted blood screening policies which avoid placing a blanket deferral on men who have sex with other men. Italy screens donors on the basis of risk, rather than sexual orientation, and in the three years following the introduction </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of the policy in 2001 the number of HIV infections through blood transfusion fell by two thirds.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Spain also screens according to risk and according to its Ministry of Health, HIV infections through blood transfusions fell to a sixth of the rate which prevailed before the policy was put in place.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Stonewall believes that screening all donors by sexual behaviour rather than solely by sexual orientation would increase stocks of blood in times of shortage by allowing previously barred gay and bisexual men to donate. It would also create a safer supply by restricting blood from unhealthy heterosexual people who are currently permitted to donate.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">2 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">These publications are available to download free from: </span><a href="http://www.healthylives.stonewall.org.uk/lgb-health/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.healthylives.stonewall.</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">o</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">rg.uk/lgb-health/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> “Stonewall welcomes 'step in right direction' on blanket blood ban”, </span><a href="http://www.stonewall.org.uk/media/current_releases/5963.asp"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.stonewall.org.uk/media/current_releases/5963.asp</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Aggiornamento </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">dei</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">casi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">di</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> AIDS </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">notificati</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> in Italia e </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">delle</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">nuove</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">diagnosi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">di</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">infezione</span><span style="font-family:'Tim